{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415077"},"attributes":{"position":46,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:02:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:02:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1409"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1409"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1409"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.02,0.08,0.72,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34260"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44769"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of difficulty swallowing. He is able to initiate swallowing, but feels as if it is difficult and painful for the food to pass a few seconds after swallowing. He points to his sternum as the location of the discomfort. This issue has been getting progressively worse, initially only affecting his swallowing of meat and bread, but now he has problems with softer food. He does not report issues swallowing liquids. He has experienced 8 kg of weight loss during this time. He reports that his previous reflux symptoms have resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, diagnosed ten years ago, and asthma, diagnosed in childhood. His medications include esomeprazole, salbutamol inhaler as needed, and fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler twice daily. He has no history of any surgeries. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and rarely drinks alcohol. His BMI is 31 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peptic stricture","Oesophageal candidiasis","Oesophageal (Schatzki) ring","Oesophageal cancer","Achalasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stem describes a patient suffering from worsening dysphagia (difficulty swallowing) with odynophagia (painful swallowing) over a relatively short time period. There can be many causes of this but, in this patient, the most concerning and unfortunately the most likely is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. Oesophageal cancer typically presents with progressive dysphagia to solids with associated weight loss. This patient also has multiple risk factors, including smoking, elevated BMI, and a history of reflux disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal candidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with odynophagia and can cause dysphagia, usually in immunocompromised patients. While this patient is on long-term inhaled corticosteroids, which can increase the risk of oesophageal candidiasis, the progressive nature of his dysphagia and significant weight loss in this case make cancer more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal (Schatzki) rings\u003C/strong\u003E are circular rings of mucosa and submucosa that form at the distal oesophagus. They typically present with intermittent dysphagia to solids or acute dysphagia due to food impaction. Typically, only hard foods such as bread and meat will be difficult to swallow or get impacted, and softer foods generally do not cause many issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to issues with the relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter. It can present initially with dysphagia to solids, but in over 70% of cases, initial presentation is dysphagia to solids and liquids and patients have symptoms for a prolonged period of time rather than a few months as in this case. Patients with achalasia may experience weight loss due to the dysphagia and can have symptoms of regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDysphagia to solids, a past medical history of GORD, older age and male sex are supportive of a \u003Cstrong\u003Epeptic stricture\u003C/strong\u003E, which is more common than oesophageal cancer. However, the rapid progression of dysphagia and significant weight loss are strongly suspicious of oesophageal cancer. Additionally, peptic strictures are fairly uncommon in individuals on acid suppressing agents, such as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient should be worked up with an urgent endoscopy to confirm the source of the dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oesophageal cancer should be considered in all patients suffering from dysphagia.","Achalasia commonly presents with dysphagia to solids and liquids."],"references":["Watts LD, Patel K. Schatzki Ring. [Updated 2020 Sep 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519022/","Momodu II, Wallen JM. Achalasia. [Updated 2021 Feb 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519515/","Lynch K. Dysphagia. Sept 2020. MSD Manual. Access at: https://www.msdmanuals.com/en-au/professional/gastrointestinal-disorders/esophageal-and-swallowing-disorders/dysphagia."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34260"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1409"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34260"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-24T16:06:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-24T16:06:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1409"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49169"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups